Evidence in page: 
Saint Gregory Seminary, also known as Mount Saint Gregory, was a high school and college seminary of the Catholic Church in Mount Washington, Cincinnati, serving the Archdiocese of Cincinnati in Ohio. Founded in 1890 by bishop William Elder along with John Albrinck and Bernard Engbers, it was closed from 1907 to 1923 due to financial difficulties. It reopened in 1923, and was permanently closed in 1980 due to declining enrollment. 

The Lombard-Romanesque campus became the site of Mount Saint Mary Seminary of the West on two occasions: From 1904 to 1923, and from 1980 to the present.

In 1969 and 1979 the junior and senior years of the high school program were phased out, leaving only the undergraduate college program remaining.

In July 1979, it was announced that St. Gregory would close, with remaining students transferring to the college program of the Pontifical College Josephinum in Worthington, Ohio. The last class of 11 students graduated from St. Gregory on May 16, 1980.

The Institutum Divi Thomae taught graduate-level science to religious sisters as well as lay people. 
From its founding in September 1935 to 1942, the Institutum Divi Thomae under the leadership of George Sperti was located at St. Gregory.

Rectors
Fr. John C. Albrinck, Ph.D., 1890–1892
Fr. J. Henry Brinkmeyer, 1892–1907
Fr. Joseph S. Seiber, 1923–1926
Fr. Urban J. Vehr, J.C.L., 1926–1929
Fr. Robert J. Sherry, J.C.D., 1929–1937
Fr. Walter A. Roddy, S.T.D., 1937–1949
Fr. William J. Gauche, S.T.D, Ph.D., 1949–1954
Fr. Robert J. Sherry, J.C.D., 1954–1961
Fr. Robert J. Krumholtz, S.T.D., 1961–1968
Fr. Daniel E. Pilarczyk, S.T.D, Ph.D., 1968–1974
Fr. Francis W. Voellmecke, S.T.L., 1974-1980

Summary: 
The college department at Saint Gregory Seminary operated initially from its founding in 1890 until a temporary closure in 1907. It reopened in 1923, eventually becoming an exclusively undergraduate college program by 1979 before permanently closing and transferring remaining students in 1980. The campus hosted graduate-level programs, notably the Mount Saint Mary Seminary of the West from 1904 to 1923 and again from 1980 to the present, as well as the Institutum Divi Thomae (teaching graduate-level science) from 1935 to 1942. The timeline of its principals, or rectors, spans from its first rector, Fr. John C. Albrinck (1890–1892), through several successors across its active periods, concluding with Fr. Francis W. Voellmecke (1974–1980).
