paragraph [ref=e729]: By 1924, Secondary Courses opened to all students, with Home Economics Secondary Courses starting from 1932. In 1936, Music Teachers Course in Piano became widely available. Eventually, the Junior Normal Course was opened to all in 1939.
paragraph [ref=e766]: In 1946, the first post-liberation graduation was held with sixty students. It was also the year where the Colegio officially received the permit for the opening of the College of Education and Liberal Arts courses.
paragraph [ref=e771]: The latter half of the century saw the Colegio expand its college and graduate level departments. In 1950, the CSI College Department introduced elementary women's education in Secondary Education levels. Then, in 1954, the Pre-Nursing Course was opened to address Nagueño's graduating their Nursing Courses at the San Juan de Dios Hospital in Pasay.
paragraph [ref=e772]: By 1955, the CSI College Department introduced elementary women's education in Elementary Education levels. In 1957, the Junior Secretarial Course sought to address young girls seeking employment, a quasi-vocational training for women's work and their Bachelor of Arts (B.A.) program, gradually introducing new courses at three-year intervals.
paragraph [ref=e777]: In 1960, B.A. in Music Education was introduced, then B.A. in Home Economics and B.A. in Management and Information Systems in 1963. In 1968, the Graduate School was formally recognized, extending the Master of Arts in both Education and Nursing that year.
paragraph [ref=e782]: Amid Marcos' martial law decreed by Proclamation 1081, Royal Decree issued in 1972 conferred Colegio de Sta. Isabel to issue honorifics for the faculty. In the same year, the Bachelor of Science in Nursing received full recognition.

Summary: 
The current principal for basic education is Simonet Barrosa, alongside vice-principal for academics Luisa Vale. The academic timeline shows that high school (secondary courses) opened to all students in 1924, followed by Home Economics in 1932. College-level education officially began in 1946 with the College of Education and Liberal Arts. The college expanded over the decades, introducing a Pre-Nursing course in 1954, and various Bachelor of Arts programs between 1957 and 1963. Finally, the Graduate School was formally recognized in 1968, offering Master of Arts degrees in Education and Nursing.
